What you are looking for is called &#39;connected components&#39;. Have a [look](https://jgrapht.org/javadoc/org.jgrapht.core/org/jgrapht/alg/connectivity/ConnectivityInspector.html) at the `ConnectivityInspector`.

To test whether your graph is connected: 
```
Graph&lt;String, DefaultEdge&gt; g = new SimpleDirectedGraph&lt;&gt;(DefaultEdge.class);
ConnectivityInspector ci = new ConnectivityInspector(g);
//Test whether the graph is connected:
ci.isConnected();
```

You can get the vertices of each of the connected components using:
`Set&lt;String&gt; vertexSets = ci.connectedSets();`
For each of these sets, you can then create a graph induced on these vertices:
```
Set&lt;String&gt; vertexSets = ci.connectedSets();
for(Set&lt;String&gt; vertexSet : vertexSets){
    Graph&lt;String, DefaultEdge&gt; subgraph = new AsSubGraph(g,vertexSet);
    //Do something with the subgraph
}
```

More information on graph connectivity can be found [here](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connectivity_(graph_theory)). For the purpose of your question you could also look into the difference between &#39;strongly&#39; and &#39;weakly&#39; connected components.

